Introduction
------------
Every team should have a security champion who can help to ensure that your product/project meets the security standards of the bank and maintains the high level of security quality our customers expect from the bank. But it does not mean that this is the only person who knows about security; everyone should understand how to create secure software and resolve security issues as they unfold in real-time. The champion is there to help with the hard bits.

Our mission is to identify and embed a security champion in a team and improve the security culture amongst the entire team. We want everyone to be aware of the importance of security in a team.

This section of the page will be updated from time to time with any useful information's from the central security team and would be shared with all security champions.

Question Mark Who is a Security Champion?
-----------------------------------------
A Security Champion is anyone with an interest/insight in security who helps amplify and upgrade the team's security awareness.  

Question Mark What does Security Champion do?
---------------------------------------------
The security champion will need to be involved in all phases of the lifecycle. Starting with the definition of new user stories and requirements elicitation/gathering, following with development guidelines and of course, security testing.

The security champion will act as a liaison between the security team and other employees. In the role of liaison, you will provide a human touch to security. You will be able to take the technical language of the security team and relay the information to their co-workers. 

It is the security champion who disseminate/share useful and important security-related information and will have the capacity to answer questions.

The security champion will have regular interruptions because you will be the single point of contact within your team. Everyone knows who to turn to. 

The security champion will be tasked with overall security awareness within the team 

A security champion will be there to convey security priorates to other members of the product/development team. The champion's responsibilities include:

Education: Staying up-to-date with the latest security practices through ongoing training with the security community/team.

Sharing: Connecting with other security champions throughout the community to share ideas and tips on current and future issues.

Inspiration: Raising awareness of security issues within the product/development teams.

Resource: Answering product/developer team questions about best practices

Escalation: Acting as the point of contact/person to escalate security issues for the security team to review

Review: Security team reviewing security issues.  

Question Mark Why do we need a Security Champion?
-------------------------------------------------
A security champion plays a vital role within a product team. They help in making decisions about security team engagement. The security champion acts as a fundamental element in assuring the process for the product and services and point of interaction within the entire team. 

Question Mark How can a security champion help within a team?
-------------------------------------------------------------
A security champion can support the team in providing coverage or skills by empowering members of his product/development team to act as a force multiplier who can pass on security best practices, answer questions, and raise security awareness. 

Question Mark What skills are needed to become a security champion?
-------------------------------------------------------------------
The skills that are required is passion, interest, and to be eager to learn. If you already know about cybersecurity, that is a plus, but it is not a mandatory skill to have. As far as you are committed to learning about it. In terms of background, people with technical skills, this is directed mainly to developers, but functional skills are needed. Analysts are also welcome.

Question Mark What is Security Culture? 
---------------------------------------
Security Culture is a set of practices that covers the below and many more

Personal Engagement

Security Awareness training 

Responsibilities

Strong Risk management policies 

Long-lived security teams

Knowledge Sharing

Open-mindedness

Management support

Benefits of having a Security Champion.
----------------------------------------
Some of the benefits of having a security champion within a team:

Scaling security through multiple teams

Engaging a non-security teams

Creating a security culture/awareness 

Question Mark What do Security Champion need to Succeed?
--------------------------------------------------------
A security champion would need the following to succeed in their role within there teams.

Clearly defined roles and responsibilities

Training, workshop, and Mentorship

Clearly defined security goals to work towards

Set time to do security task 

Realistic Expectations

A career pathway/progression 

Question Mark What are the priorities for teams to have a Security Champion?
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
It depends on the security knowledge level of your team. If it is high, you may not need one. If it is low, you definitely do need a security champion. 
